const P={home:{title:"NexaFlow Platform",subtitle:"User Manual & Documentation",icon:I.Home},getting_started:{title:"Getting Started",icon:I.Rocket,sections:[{id:"gs-1",title:"Platform Overview",content:"NexaFlow is a unified design & technology workspace that brings together file management, project tracking, team collaboration, AI assistance, workflow automation, creative proofing, client portals, and resource planning into one self-hosted platform. Built specifically for creative agencies, software teams, and tech companies, it provides a fully secure environment where your data stays on infrastructure you control.\n\nThe platform is accessible through any modern web browser — we recommend the latest versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari, or Edge. Mobile applications for iOS and Android provide full functionality on the go, while native desktop sync clients for Windows, macOS, and Linux keep your local files continuously synchronized with the server.\n\nNexaFlow is available in three editions: Community (free, self-hosted), Enterprise On-Premises (self-hosted with enterprise add-ons and support), and Enterprise Cloud (hosted by NexaFlow in EU or US data centers). All editions support unlimited projects. Enterprise editions add advanced features like SAML SSO, LDAP group sync, audit log immutability, priority support, and the AI co-pilot module."},{id:"gs-2",title:"Creating Your Account & First Login",content:"Navigate to your organization's NexaFlow URL (e.g., workspace.yourcompany.com) and enter the credentials provided by your administrator. If your organization uses Single Sign-On (SSO), click the SSO button to authenticate through your identity provider (Okta, Azure AD, OneLogin, etc.).\n\nOn your very first login, an onboarding wizard walks you through initial setup: uploading a profile photo and setting your display name, choosing your preferred language and timezone (60+ languages supported), selecting notification delivery preferences, accepting pending project invitations, and optionally installing the desktop sync client.\n\nWe strongly recommend enabling Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) during onboarding. Navigate to Settings then Security then Two-Factor Authentication to set up TOTP (Google Authenticator, Authy) or a hardware key (YubiKey, FIDO2). Once enabled, you'll need your second factor each time you log in from a new device."},{id:"gs-3",title:"Navigating the Main Interface",content:"The NexaFlow interface is organized into distinct functional areas:\n\nApps Selection Menu — Located in the upper-left corner, this horizontal menu bar provides one-click access to every enabled module: Dashboard, Files, Projects, Boards, Calendar, Chat, Wiki, Time Tracking, Reports, and any additional modules your administrator has enabled. You can pin, reorder, and hide apps to customize the menu.\n\nApplication View — The large central workspace that displays content for the currently selected module. This area adapts its layout based on the active module — grid view for files, table/board view for projects, timeline for Gantt charts, conversation view for chat.\n\nNavigation Bar — Positioned above the Application View, this bar provides breadcrumb-style navigation for moving quickly up through folder hierarchies or project structures. It also hosts the Create New button and module-specific actions.\n\nUniversal Search — Press Ctrl+K or Cmd+K to open the command palette. Search across all modules simultaneously: files, work packages, wiki pages, contacts, calendar events, and chat messages. Use type: filters to narrow results.\n\nQuick Actions Bar — Press Ctrl+/ to open the quick actions overlay. Type commands like create task, upload file, start timer, or open project X for keyboard-driven workflow."},{id:"gs-4",title:"Personal Dashboard & Widgets",content:"Your personal dashboard is the first screen you see after login. It aggregates information from across all your projects into a single customizable view.\n\nDefault widgets include: Activity Stream (recent actions across your projects), My Tasks (work packages assigned to you sorted by priority and due date), Upcoming Events (next 7 days of calendar entries), Recent Files (documents you recently accessed or modified), Time Tracking Summary (hours logged this week), and News Feed (announcements from your projects).\n\nCustomize the dashboard by clicking Edit Dashboard in the top-right corner. Add, remove, rearrange, and resize widgets using a drag-and-drop grid editor. Each widget is independently configurable — set its data source, filters, display options, date range, and auto-refresh interval.\n\nAdditional widget types include: Project Health Overview (traffic-light status for all your projects), Sprint Burndown Chart (for agile teams), OKR Progress Tracker, Bookmarked Items, Weather and Time Zone Widget (for distributed teams), Embedded Web Page (iframe any URL), and Custom Metric Cards (display API-driven numbers from external systems).\n\nDashboard layouts can be saved as named presets and shared with your team by exporting as a template that other users can import."},{id:"gs-5",title:"Keyboard Shortcuts & Accessibility",content:"NexaFlow is designed for keyboard-first workflows. Press ? from any screen to view the complete shortcuts reference overlay. Key shortcuts include:\n\nCtrl+K — Open universal search and command palette. Ctrl+/ — Open quick actions bar. Ctrl+N — Create new item in current context. G then D — Go to Dashboard. G then F — Go to Files. G then P — Go to Projects. G then C — Go to Calendar. Escape — Close current modal or go back.\n\nWithin work package lists: J/K — Move selection up/down. Enter — Open selected item. X — Toggle selection for bulk actions.\n\nAccessibility features: Full keyboard navigation for all functions using Tab, Enter, and Escape. ARIA landmarks and labels for screen reader compatibility (JAWS, NVDA, VoiceOver). High-contrast themes available in appearance settings. Configurable font size scaling (75%–200%). Reduced motion mode that disables all animations. Focus indicators visible on all interactive elements. Skip-to-content links on every page. WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance target."},{id:"gs-6",title:"Installing Desktop & Mobile Clients",content:"Desktop Sync Client — Available for Windows (10+), macOS (11+), and Linux (Ubuntu, Fedora, openSUSE, Arch). The client provides: Selective sync — Choose specific folders and projects to sync locally. Virtual files — See all server files in your file manager without downloading them; files are fetched on-demand when opened (Windows and macOS). Bandwidth throttling — Set upload and download speed limits. Conflict resolution — When the same file is modified both locally and on the server, the client saves both versions and notifies you. Multi-account support — Connect to multiple NexaFlow instances from a single client. Status overlay icons — File sync status shown directly on file icons in your native file manager.\n\nMobile Apps — The iOS and Android apps provide: file browsing and downloading, offline access to marked files, photo and video auto-upload from camera roll, document scanning using the phone camera, push notifications for all event types, work package viewing and editing, chat messaging and voice calls, and biometric authentication (Face ID, Touch ID, fingerprint).\n\nBoth desktop and mobile clients can be deployed and configured centrally using MDM (Mobile Device Management) systems for enterprise rollouts."}]},file_management:{title:"File Management",icon:I.Folder,sections:[{id:"fm-1",title:"Files Module Overview",content:"The Files module is your central document hub. Create, preview, edit, delete, share, and version files directly through the web interface. The module supports virtually any file type, with in-browser preview for common formats: images (JPG, PNG, GIF, WebP, SVG, HEIC), documents (PDF, DOCX, XLSX, PPTX, ODF), text files (TXT, MD, CSV, JSON, XML, YAML), video (MP4, WebM, MOV), audio (MP3, WAV, FLAC, OGG), and code files (with syntax highlighting for 50+ languages).\n\nThe left sidebar provides filter views: All Files (your complete file tree), Favorites (items you've starred), Shared with You, Shared with Others, Shared by Link, Recently Modified, Tags (filter by color-coded tags), Deleted Files (trash with restore), and External Storage (connected external backends).\n\nThe main file area supports three view modes: List View (compact table with columns for name, size, modified date, and share status), Grid View (thumbnail previews ideal for image-heavy folders), and Gallery View (full-width image carousel for photo reviews). Sort by any column; filter by file type, date range, size, or tags."},{id:"fm-2",title:"Uploading, Creating & Organizing",content:"Upload files by clicking the + button and selecting Upload Files or Upload Folder, or simply drag and drop from your native file manager. The web uploader supports resumable uploads — if your connection drops, the upload continues from where it left off rather than restarting. Maximum file size is configured by your administrator (default 16 GB per file).\n\nCreate new content directly: plain text files, Markdown documents, rich-text documents (with collaborative editing), spreadsheets, presentations, diagrams (using the built-in diagram editor), and from templates your organization has configured.\n\nOrganize with folders, color-coded tags, and favorites. Move files by dragging them between folders or using the right-click context menu. Batch operations (move, copy, delete, download, tag, share) work on multiple selections — hold Ctrl/Cmd and click to select multiple items, or use Shift+Click for range selection."},{id:"fm-3",title:"Sharing & Permissions",content:"Select any file or folder and open the sharing panel to manage access:\n\nInternal Sharing — Type a username, group name, or email address to share within your organization. Permission levels include: Viewer (can view and download), Editor (can view, download, and modify), Custom (administrator-defined permission sets). Additional options per share: can re-share, expiration date, and a personal note.\n\nPublic Link Sharing — Generate unique URLs accessible by anyone with the link. Each link has independent settings: password protection, expiration date, download or view-only, upload-only mode (drop box), and access count limit. Create multiple links for the same resource with different configurations.\n\nFederated Sharing — Share with users on other NexaFlow or compatible instances by entering their federated ID (user@other-instance.com). Files appear in the recipient's Shared with You view.\n\nEmail Sharing — Enter external email addresses to send sharing invitations. Recipients access content through a web viewer without needing an account. Track delivery and access activity.\n\nShare Audit Trail — Every share event is logged: who shared what, with whom, when, and what permissions were granted. The Shared Overview page shows all active shares across the entire instance."},{id:"fm-4",title:"Version History & Trash Recovery",content:"Every file modification automatically creates a new version. The Versions tab shows the complete history: version number, modification timestamp, author, file size, and optional comment.\n\nVersion actions: Preview any historical version in the browser. Download a specific version. Restore a previous version as the current one. Compare two versions side-by-side for text-based files (diff view with additions in green and deletions in red). Name specific versions with labels for easy reference (e.g., Final Approved, Pre-Client Review).\n\nVersion retention policies are configurable: keep all versions, keep for a specific period, or keep a maximum number per file. Manual pin protects specific versions from automatic cleanup.\n\nDeleted files move to the Trash, where they remain for the configured retention period (default 30 days). Restore individual files or entire folder trees. The Trash shows: file name, original location, deletion date, deleted by, and file size. Empty manually to reclaim storage."},{id:"fm-5",title:"WebDAV, Desktop Sync & External Storage",content:"WebDAV Access — Mount your NexaFlow files as a network drive. Your personal WebDAV URL follows the format: https://your-instance.com/remote.php/dav/files/USERNAME/. Compatible with Windows, macOS, and Linux file managers. Use app-specific passwords for WebDAV connections.\n\nDesktop Sync — The desktop client provides bidirectional real-time synchronization. Configure per-folder sync settings, use virtual files for on-demand download, and set bandwidth scheduling and pause/resume controls.\n\nExternal Storage Backends — Administrators can mount external services that appear as regular folders: Amazon S3 (and S3-compatible), SMB/CIFS network shares, SFTP/FTP, Google Drive, Dropbox, OneDrive/SharePoint, OpenStack Swift, and WebDAV servers. External storage files do not count against user quotas."},{id:"fm-6",title:"Encryption & Data Protection",content:"Server-Side Encryption — When enabled, all files are encrypted with AES-256 before being written to storage. Transparent to users; the platform handles encryption on upload and decryption on download. Recovery keys allow administrators to decrypt files if a user loses access.\n\nEnd-to-End Encryption (E2EE) — For maximum security, enable E2E encryption on specific folders. Files are encrypted on the client device before upload; the server never sees unencrypted content. Only devices with the private key can decrypt. E2E folders have limitations: no server-side preview, no full-text search, no collaborative editing, and access only through clients.\n\nFile Access Control Rules — Administrators can block sharing outside the organization for files tagged Confidential, prevent downloads from mobile devices, require watermarking on PDF downloads, restrict to specific IP ranges, and enforce retention locks for legal holds.\n\nData Loss Prevention (DLP) — Scan uploaded files for sensitive content patterns (credit card numbers, SSNs, medical records) and automatically apply classification tags, restrict sharing, or alert administrators."},{id:"fm-7",title:"Smart Tags & Auto-Classification",content:"Tags are color-coded labels you can apply to any file or folder. Create personal tags (visible only to you) or collaborative tags (visible to everyone with access). Assign multiple tags to a single item. Filter your file view by one or more tags.\n\nAutomated Tagging Rules — Set up rules that automatically apply tags based on conditions: tag all files in the Contracts folder as Legal, tag files larger than 100 MB as Large File, tag files shared externally as External.\n\nAI-Powered Auto-Classification — When the AI module is enabled, NexaFlow automatically analyzes uploaded documents and suggests tags, categories, and metadata based on content analysis. Accept, modify, or dismiss AI suggestions.\n\nSmart Folders — Create virtual folders that automatically aggregate files matching tag combinations, metadata criteria, or search queries. A smart folder for Q1 2026 Deliverables might combine files tagged Q1 + Deliverable across all projects. Smart folders update dynamically."}]},project_management:{title:"Project Management",icon:I.Board,sections:[{id:"pm-1",title:"Projects Overview",content:"The Projects module provides enterprise-grade project management. Each project is an independent workspace with its own members, roles, enabled modules, custom fields, work package types, and workflows. This modular architecture lets you configure each project to match its methodology — Scrum, Kanban, Waterfall, hybrid, or custom.\n\nProject hierarchies support parent-child relationships: nest sub-projects under parent projects to model organizational structures, client accounts, or program portfolios. Child projects can inherit settings from parents or override them.\n\nThe Global Projects page lists all projects with filterable columns: name, status, health indicator, lead, dates, progress, and member count. The project hierarchy view shows nesting as an expandable tree.\n\nEvery project has a configurable Overview page that serves as its landing page. Add widgets: project description, key metrics, activity stream, work package charts, team list, recent documents, and custom content blocks."},{id:"pm-2",title:"Work Packages in Detail",content:"Work packages are the universal work item in NexaFlow. They represent tasks, features, bugs, user stories, epics, milestones, phases, risks, decisions, change requests, or any trackable item.\n\nCore Fields: Type (determines icon, available fields, and workflow), Subject (title), Description (rich text with embedded images, tables, code blocks), Status (follows workflow transitions), Priority (Immediate, High, Normal, Low, custom), Assignee, Accountable (distinct from assignee), Start Date and Due Date, Estimated Time, Spent Time (from time entries), Progress (manual or auto-calculated from children), Version/Sprint, Category, and up to 50 custom fields per type.\n\nRelationships: Parent-child (break epics into stories into tasks). Predecessor/successor (finish-to-start, start-to-start, finish-to-finish, start-to-finish with optional lag). Related (informational). Blocks/blocked by. Duplicates/duplicated by.\n\nActivity and Comments: Every field change is logged with before/after values. Comments support rich text, @mentions, and file attachments. Comment reactions (emoji). Subscribe to receive notifications.\n\nWatchers: Add yourself or others as watchers for notifications without being assigned."},{id:"pm-3",title:"Agile Boards (Kanban & Scrum)",content:"Boards provide drag-and-drop visual management with multiple board types:\n\nStatus Board — Columns map to work package statuses. Dragging a card changes its status and triggers workflow automations. Column WIP limits prevent overloading stages.\n\nAssignee Board — Columns represent team members. Visualize workload distribution. Headers show total estimated hours and task count.\n\nVersion/Sprint Board — Columns represent iterations. Plan sprints by dragging items from backlog. See total story points and capacity per sprint.\n\nCustom Attribute Board — Build boards based on any field: priority, category, custom fields, or project.\n\nBoard Cards display: type icon with color coding, title, assignee avatar(s), priority indicator, due date (with overdue highlighting), story points, progress bar, and attachment/comment badges. Click a card to open inline detail panel.\n\nSwimlanes — Group cards into horizontal lanes by any attribute. For example, group by priority within a Status Board.\n\nBoard Filters — Apply filters to show only specific subsets: my tasks, tasks due this week, tasks in a specific category, or any combination."},{id:"pm-4",title:"Gantt Charts & Timeline Planning",content:"The Gantt chart provides an interactive visual timeline. Work packages appear as horizontal bars with dependency arrows connecting related items.\n\nInteractive Features: Drag bars to reschedule. Drag edges to change duration. Click and drag between bars to create dependencies. Multi-select and move together. Undo/redo for all modifications.\n\nZoom Levels: Day, Week, Month, Quarter, Year. Auto-zoom selects the best level for the visible date range.\n\nCritical Path — Highlight the longest chain of dependent tasks determining earliest project completion. Any delay to a critical-path item delays the entire project.\n\nBaselines — Save schedule snapshots. Display baseline alongside current schedule showing slippage with visual indicators.\n\nMilestones appear as diamond markers. They represent key dates with zero duration.\n\nResource Leveling — Automatically adjust schedules to avoid overallocating team members by shifting lower-priority tasks.\n\nExport and Print — Export as PDF (customizable paper size) or PNG for presentations."},{id:"pm-5",title:"Roadmap, Versions & Releases",content:"The Roadmap provides a high-level view of planned releases organized by version. Each version shows name, target date, description, status (Open, Locked, Closed), and progress bar calculated from assigned work packages.\n\nSprint Backlog view shows all work packages assigned to a version/sprint with total story points, estimated hours, and completion metrics.\n\nRelease Notes Generation — Automatically generate release notes from a version's completed work packages, grouped by type (features, bug fixes, improvements). Publish to wiki or external changelog.\n\nVersion Comparison — Compare two versions side by side: items planned vs. delivered, velocity metrics, and scope change analysis."},{id:"pm-6",title:"Project Templates & Variables",content:"Templates capture a project's complete configuration for reuse: enabled modules, work package types and workflows, custom fields, board layouts, wiki structure, category lists, version definitions, default work packages, notification settings, and file folder structure.\n\nTo create a template: set up a project with desired structure, then go to Project Settings and Set as Template. Templates appear in the template library when creating new projects.\n\nTemplate Variables — Define placeholders like {{client_name}} and {{kick_off_date}} that are filled when creating a new project from the template. Variables propagate to subjects, descriptions, wiki content, and folder names.\n\nCross-Project Workflows — Create multi-project templates that generate entire project hierarchies with inter-project dependencies."}]},collaboration:{title:"Collaboration & Communication",icon:I.Chat,sections:[{id:"co-1",title:"Real-Time Chat (Talk)",content:"The Talk module provides integrated messaging without external tools. Create one-on-one conversations, group chats, or public channels organized by topic, project, or team.\n\nMessage Features: Rich text formatting, emoji reactions, file and image sharing (drag and drop), voice messages, message replies and threads, read receipts, message editing and deletion, pinned messages, and full-text message search.\n\nConversation Types: One-on-One, Group (invite specific members), Public Channel, Password-Protected Channel, and Guest-Accessible Channel (external participants join via link).\n\nPresence Indicators show online/offline/away/do-not-disturb status. Set custom status messages visible to all users.\n\nMessage Bots and Integrations — Receive notifications from GitHub, GitLab, Jira, or monitoring systems in channels. Create webhooks that post messages when events occur. Use / commands to interact with integrations."},{id:"co-2",title:"Video Conferencing & Screen Sharing",content:"Start a call from any Talk conversation. Supported capabilities:\n\nCall Types: One-on-one voice, one-on-one video, group voice, and group video (up to 75 participants with High-Performance Backend; up to 6 without).\n\nDuring a Call: Toggle camera and microphone. Switch cameras. Blur or replace background with custom images. Share entire screen, specific window, or browser tab. In-call chat. Raise hand. Pin a participant's video.\n\nRecording — Capture all audio and video including screen shares. Recording notifications shown to all participants. Recordings saved to conversation file storage.\n\nBreakout Rooms — Split participants into smaller groups. Assign manually, randomly, or let participants self-select. Broadcast to all rooms. Set auto-close timer.\n\nSIP/H.323 Bridge — Enterprise edition integrates with traditional telephony. Dial into meetings from regular phones using number and PIN."},{id:"co-3",title:"Collaborative Document Editing",content:"Real-time collaborative editing allows multiple team members to work on the same document simultaneously. Each person's cursor appears in a distinct color with their name label.\n\nSupported Types: Rich Text Documents (headings, tables, images, lists, footnotes), Spreadsheets (formulas, charts, pivot tables, conditional formatting), Presentations (layouts, transitions, animations, speaker notes), and Diagrams (flowcharts, network diagrams, wireframes, org charts).\n\nEditor Features: Full formatting toolbar, / slash commands, @mention users, link to work packages with #1234, table of contents generation, change tracking, comment threads anchored to text selections, export to PDF/DOCX/ODT.\n\nOffline Editing — The desktop client supports offline editing. Changes queue and sync when connectivity returns. Conflicts resolved through three-way merge."},{id:"co-4",title:"Wiki & Knowledge Base",content:"Each project can maintain a wiki for structured documentation. Wikis support hierarchical page trees for project documentation, technical specifications, API references, runbooks, meeting notes, and knowledge bases.\n\nWiki Editor Features: WYSIWYG and Markdown modes. Slash commands. Table of Contents macro. Embedded Work Package Table macro (dynamic filtering). Child Pages macro. Create Work Package button macro. Code blocks with syntax highlighting for 50+ languages. Mermaid diagram rendering. LaTeX/KaTeX math formulas.\n\nPage Versioning — Every edit creates a version. Compare any two versions with visual diff. Restore previous versions. Lock pages to prevent edits during major changes.\n\nCross-Referencing — Link to other pages with [[Page Name]], work packages with #1234, users with @username, and files with a picker. All references are bidirectional.\n\nWiki Templates — Create page templates for recurring structures (meeting notes, retrospectives, incident post-mortems). Global Wiki available across all projects for company-wide documentation."},{id:"co-5",title:"Meetings, Agendas & Minutes",content:"Plan, conduct, and document meetings with full lifecycle management:\n\nBefore the Meeting: Create with title, date/time, duration, location (physical or video call link). Build agenda collaboratively. Send agenda to invitees.\n\nDuring the Meeting: Follow structured agenda with timer per item. Take notes within each item. Record decisions and create action items that instantly become assigned work packages. Track attendance.\n\nAfter the Meeting: Minutes saved automatically. Participants receive summary email with key decisions and action items. Meeting series support recurring meetings carrying forward unresolved items.\n\nMeeting Dashboard — View all upcoming and past meetings. My Action Items view aggregates tasks created from meetings across all projects."},{id:"co-6",title:"News, Forums & Announcements",content:"News Module — Project-level broadcast for announcements with rich text, comments, and pinning.\n\nForums Module — Structured discussion boards within projects. Create topic categories (General, Technical, Ideas, Questions). Support rich text, file attachments, @mentions. Pin threads, close resolved discussions.\n\nForums provide persistent, searchable, organized discussions that serve as a knowledge record. Unlike chat messages that scroll away, forum threads remain easily discoverable and categorized.\n\nAnnouncement Banners — Administrators display global banners across every page for system maintenance notices, policy changes, or celebrations. Support rich text, links, and scheduled start/end dates."}]},user_management:{title:"Team & User Management",icon:I.Users,sections:[{id:"um-1",title:"User Accounts & Profiles",content:"Each person has a unique account with a Login Name (immutable identifier) and a Full Name (display name). Administrators create accounts by entering email, first name, and last name. Users receive activation email to set their own password.\n\nProfile Fields: Avatar, full name, email (primary + additional), job title, department, organization, phone, language, timezone, and custom profile fields.\n\nAccount Statuses: Active (normal access), Invited (pending activation), Locked Temporarily (auto after failed logins, auto-unlocks), Locked Permanently (admin disabled), Registered (pending admin approval).\n\nDisabling vs. Deleting: Disabling preserves all data while preventing login. External shares are suspended but internal shares work. Deleting permanently removes the account. Disabling is recommended for audit trail integrity.\n\nSelf-Registration — Options: open registration, email-domain restriction, manual approval, and invitation-only."},{id:"um-2",title:"Roles, Permissions & Workflows",content:"Access control uses role-based permissions with 100+ individual permission toggles organized by module.\n\nBuilt-In Roles: Administrator — Full system access. Project Admin — Full access within their project. Member — Standard participant. Reader — View-only. Non-Member — Default for logged-in users not added to a project. Anonymous — For unauthenticated visitors to public projects.\n\nCustom Roles — Create tailored roles: Client Stakeholder (view but not edit), External Contractor (edit assigned tasks only), QA Tester (change status to specific values only).\n\nWorkflow Designer — Define allowed status transitions per work package type per role. Example: only Project Admins can move from In Review to Approved.\n\nPermission Dependencies — Granting edit permission automatically includes view permission. The system prevents inconsistent configurations."},{id:"um-3",title:"Groups, LDAP & Placeholder Users",content:"Groups simplify access management. Assigning a group to a project grants all members the group's role.\n\nGroup Types: Standard (manually managed), LDAP-Synchronized (mirrors corporate directory), Self-Service (users join/leave freely).\n\nGroup Administrators — Designated users managing membership within their groups without full admin privileges.\n\nPlaceholder Users — Dummy accounts representing roles (Designer, QA Lead). Use in templates, replace with real people when project launches. Don't count against licenses.\n\nOrganization Structure — Define hierarchy (Company, Division, Department, Team) mapped to groups for cascading notifications and capacity planning."},{id:"um-4",title:"Authentication, SSO & Security",content:"Layered authentication support:\n\nLocal Authentication — Configurable policies: minimum length, complexity, expiration, password history, strength meter.\n\nLDAP / Active Directory — Users authenticate with corporate credentials. Import user attributes. LDAP filters and group sync.\n\nSAML 2.0 / SSO — Integrate with Okta, Azure AD, OneLogin, PingIdentity, Google Workspace, KeyCloak. Attributes from SAML assertion populate profile fields.\n\nTwo-Factor Authentication — TOTP apps, hardware security keys (FIDO2/WebAuthn), backup codes. Enforce for all users, specific groups, or roles. Grace period for setup.\n\nSession Management — View active sessions (device, browser, IP, last active). Revoke sessions. Configurable timeouts. IP-based restrictions.\n\nApp Passwords — Dedicated passwords for third-party clients without exposing main password. Named, tracked, individually revocable."}]},calendar_time:{title:"Calendar & Time Tracking",icon:I.Cal,sections:[{id:"ct-1",title:"Calendar Module",content:"Day, week, month, and agenda views. Events color-coded by source.\n\nMultiple Sources: Personal, project, shared team, and subscribed external calendars.\n\nWork Package Integration — Due dates and milestones from Projects appear on your calendar.\n\nAvailability View — See attendees' free/busy status when scheduling. System suggests optimal slots. Resource booking for meeting rooms and equipment.\n\nCalendar Sharing — Share with specific people or groups: Free/Busy Only, Read Access, or Edit Access.\n\nCalDAV Sync — Compatible with Apple Calendar, Thunderbird, GNOME Calendar. Import/export iCalendar format. Subscribe to external calendars by URL. Bidirectional sync with Google Workspace and Microsoft 365."},{id:"ct-2",title:"Time Tracking & Timesheets",content:"Log time on any work package using multiple methods:\n\nTimer — Click clock icon to start a running timer that persists across navigation and browser sessions.\n\nManual Entry — Add time entry with date, hours, activity type, and comment.\n\nTimesheet View — Weekly grid: days across top, work packages down side. Fill in hours for fastest batch entry.\n\nActivity Types — Development, Design, Management, QA/Testing, Research, Documentation, Support, Travel, and custom types.\n\nReminders — Daily notifications if you haven't logged minimum expected hours.\n\nApproval Workflows — Enterprise edition supports time entry approval routing to designated approvers. Approved entries are locked.\n\nOvertime and Leave Tracking — Track overtime against contracted hours. Integrate with leave management for vacation, sick days, and other absences."},{id:"ct-3",title:"Budgets & Cost Management",content:"Create project budgets with two cost categories: Labor Costs (from time entries times hourly rates) and Unit/Material Costs (software licenses, hardware, subcontractor invoices, travel).\n\nHourly Rates — Per user, per role, per project. Date-effective ranges for rate changes without affecting historical calculations.\n\nBudget Views: Planned vs. Actual with variance. Burn rate analysis. Forecast completion cost. Breakdown by category/phase/member. S-curve for earned value management.\n\nCost Reports — Filterable by project, date, user, activity, category. Export to CSV or PDF. Schedule automatic generation and email delivery.\n\nMulti-Currency Support — Enter costs in different currencies with centralized exchange rates.\n\nExpense Tracking — Submit individual expense items with receipt attachments through approval workflow."},{id:"ct-4",title:"Reports, Analytics & Dashboards",content:"Work Package Reports — Configurable tables with columns, filters, grouping, sorting, and aggregation. Save as named queries.\n\nCharts: Bar (grouped/stacked), line (trends), pie/donut (distribution), area (cumulative), scatter (correlation), heat maps (activity density).\n\nBurndown and Burnup Charts — Track remaining or completed work against ideal trend lines across sprints.\n\nVelocity Chart — Story points completed per sprint over time for forecasting capacity.\n\nCumulative Flow Diagram — Visualize work moving through stages. Identify bottlenecks.\n\nCustom Dashboard Builder — Drag-and-drop with 20+ widget types. Create operational, executive, and personal dashboards. Share with teams or embed in wiki pages.\n\nScheduled Reports — Auto-generate daily/weekly/monthly and email to recipients with PDF/CSV attachments."}]},ai_assistant:{title:"AI Co-Pilot",icon:I.Ai,sections:[{id:"ai-1",title:"AI Assistant Overview",content:"NexaFlow's AI Co-Pilot is an integrated artificial intelligence assistant that enhances productivity across every module. The AI runs on your infrastructure (no data sent to external services), ensuring complete data privacy and compliance.\n\nAccess from anywhere: click the sparkle icon in the toolbar, press Ctrl+Shift+A, or type /ai in any text input. The AI understands context — when invoked from a work package, it accesses that item's details, history, and related items.\n\nThree Modes: Chat Mode (conversational Q&A about your projects and data), Action Mode (performs tasks like creating work packages, generating reports, drafting documents), and Suggestion Mode (proactively offers recommendations as you work).\n\nData Privacy: All processing is local on your NexaFlow instance. No data transmitted to external AI services. Administrators control which users can access AI features and can disable it for specific sensitive projects."},{id:"ai-2",title:"Smart Summarization & Writing",content:"Summarize Anything — Select any long document, meeting transcript, email thread, wiki page, or work package discussion for a concise summary. Control length: one-liner, paragraph, executive summary, or detailed brief. Automatically identifies key decisions, action items, risks, and deadlines.\n\nDocument Drafting — Describe what you need and the AI generates a first draft: project proposals, status reports, technical specifications, test plans, client emails, release notes, or SOPs. Select a tone: formal, casual, technical, or executive.\n\nTranslation — Translate documents, wiki pages, or messages between 60+ languages. Preserves formatting, links, and embedded references.\n\nGrammar and Style — Select text for grammar checking, clarity improvements, or tone adjustment. Adapts content to different audiences (technical to non-technical, internal to client-facing).\n\nTemplate Generation — Describe a repeating process and the AI creates a structured template with sections, prompts, and example content."},{id:"ai-3",title:"Predictive Analytics & Risk Detection",content:"Project Health Predictions — Analyzes velocity, burndown trends, dependency chains, and historical patterns to predict: whether sprints will meet targets, which tasks risk missing due dates, which team members may be overloaded, and budget overrun likelihood.\n\nRisk Alerts — Proactive notifications when: critical-path tasks stall, dependency predecessors fall behind, team member utilization exceeds sustainable levels, or budget burn rate exceeds plan.\n\nSmart Scheduling Suggestions — When creating work packages, suggests optimal assignees based on: skill match (inferred from past completed tasks), current workload, calendar availability, and historical performance.\n\nAnomaly Detection — Monitors for unusual patterns: sudden bug report spikes, drops in commit activity, repeated re-opening of completed tasks, or time entries deviating significantly from estimates."},{id:"ai-4",title:"Natural Language Queries",content:"Ask your data questions in plain language:\n\nHow many bugs were closed this sprint? — Returns count with breakdown by severity and assignee.\n\nWhat's blocking the v2.0 release? — Identifies blocking dependencies and overdue items.\n\nShow me everything John worked on last week — Displays work package updates, time entries, and file contributions.\n\nCompare our velocity for the last 5 sprints — Generates velocity chart with trend analysis.\n\nDraft a status update for the client about Project Apollo — Creates formatted summary with progress, risks, and upcoming milestones.\n\nCreate a task for Sarah to review the design mockups by Friday, high priority — Creates a work package with all specified fields.\n\nThe AI also answers meta-questions: How do I create a Gantt chart? generates a step-by-step guide."},{id:"ai-5",title:"AI Content Analysis",content:"Document Intelligence — Upload contracts, proposals, or technical documents. The AI extracts: parties involved, dates and deadlines, monetary amounts, obligations and deliverables, risk clauses, and defined terms. Extracted data maps to work packages or custom fields.\n\nImage and Design Analysis — Upload screenshots, wireframes, or mockups. The AI describes visual content, identifies UI elements, suggests accessibility improvements, detects design system inconsistencies, and generates work packages for issues found.\n\nMeeting Transcript Analysis — Upload recording transcriptions. The AI identifies action items, decisions, questions, and participants. Automatically create follow-up work packages with assigned owners and due dates.\n\nSentiment Analysis — For feedback from forms, surveys, or forums, analyzes sentiment and topics. Dashboard widget shows satisfaction trends and most-mentioned themes.\n\nCode Review Assistance — Review code snippets shared in work packages or wiki pages, suggesting improvements, identifying bugs, and checking for security vulnerabilities."}]},automation:{title:"Workflow Automation",icon:I.Zap,sections:[{id:"au-1",title:"Automation Engine Overview",content:"The Workflow Automation Engine lets you automate repetitive tasks using a visual trigger-condition-action system:\n\nTrigger — The event that starts automation: work package created, status changed, field modified, due date approaching, file uploaded, user added, time entry submitted, form submitted, schedule (daily/weekly/monthly), or webhook received.\n\nConditions — Optional filters: work package type is Bug AND priority is High, assigned user is in group Developers, project name contains Client, or any combination using AND/OR logic.\n\nActions — What happens when triggered: change field values, send notifications (email, chat, push), create work packages, add comments, move to different projects, apply tags, start approval workflows, make API calls, update parent statuses based on children, or run custom scripts.\n\nAutomations are configured at project or global level. Each has an audit log showing every execution: when it fired, what triggered it, conditions evaluated, and actions taken."},{id:"au-2",title:"Common Automation Recipes",content:"Pre-built recipes you can enable and customize:\n\nAuto-Assign by Type — Bugs go to QA lead. Design tasks go to next available designer based on workload.\n\nDue Date Notifications — 3 days before: remind assignee. 1 day after: escalate to project manager. 1 week overdue: notify project sponsor.\n\nStatus Chain Reactions — All epic children Done: set epic to Done. Blocking task completed: notify blocked task assignees. Task enters In Review: assign to designated reviewer.\n\nNew Member Onboarding — When user added to project: share Getting Started wiki page, create onboarding checklist work package, send welcome message in project chat, add to notification group.\n\nFile-Based Triggers — File uploaded to Deliverables folder: create review work package and notify project manager. Contract PDF uploaded: trigger AI to extract dates and create milestones.\n\nScheduled — Every Monday: generate weekly status summary. Every sprint end: create next sprint and copy unfinished items. Monthly: generate and email budget reports."},{id:"au-3",title:"Webhooks, API & Integrations",content:"Outgoing Webhooks — POST JSON to external URLs when events occur. Customize payload format and auth headers. Sync with CRMs, notify Slack, trigger CI/CD pipelines.\n\nIncoming Webhooks — Receive data from external systems. Project-specific endpoints accept JSON and map to actions: create work packages from alerts, update statuses from CI/CD, import customer feedback.\n\nREST API — Full programmatic access. CRUD on all entities, query filters, file upload/download, batch operations, pagination, and WebSocket subscriptions.\n\nAPI Authentication: OAuth 2.0, API keys (configurable scopes), session-based. Rate limiting: 100 requests/minute default.\n\nIntegration Marketplace — GitHub/GitLab, Jenkins/CircleCI/GitHub Actions, Slack/Teams/Mattermost, email-to-task, Zapier/Make/n8n (5000+ apps)."}]},client_portal:{title:"Client Portal",icon:I.Globe,sections:[{id:"cp-1",title:"Client Portal Overview",content:"Provides a controlled, branded interface for external stakeholders — clients, vendors, partners — to view project status, review deliverables, submit feedback, and approve work without needing a full NexaFlow account.\n\nEnable per-project in Project Settings. Configure exposed information: work package progress (filtered view), milestone timeline, shared documents, budget summaries (optional), and feedback forms.\n\nClient Accounts — Invite by email. Lightweight accounts, free, don't count against licenses. Clients see only explicitly shared content.\n\nBranding — Customize with your or your client's logo, color scheme, and custom domain. Different branding per client."},{id:"cp-2",title:"Status Exposure & Approvals",content:"Work Package Visibility — Choose which types, statuses, and fields are visible. Show Deliverable and Milestone types; hide Bug and Internal Task.\n\nClient-Visible Timeline — Simplified Gantt showing only client-relevant milestones. Internal tasks, dependencies, and team details hidden.\n\nApproval Workflows — Upload deliverables for client review. Clients can: approve, request changes (with annotated feedback on documents/images), or reject (with explanation). Status reflected in internal work packages.\n\nClient Dashboard — Project health overview, next milestone countdown, percentage complete, deliverables ready for review, and message widget.\n\nActivity Log — Curated feed showing deliverables shared, milestones completed, feedback responses, and status changes. Internal activity excluded."},{id:"cp-3",title:"Feedback & Request Management",content:"Feedback Forms — Customizable forms: satisfaction surveys, feature requests, change requests, bug reports. Support text, dropdowns, ratings, file upload, and conditional logic.\n\nRequest Queue — Submissions appear in internal-only queue. Triage: convert to work packages, assign, set priority, track resolution. Clients see status (Received, Under Review, In Progress, Resolved) without internal details.\n\nAnnotation and Markup — Clients annotate shared images, PDFs, and documents directly in the portal. Draw circles, arrows, text notes on specific areas.\n\nCommunication Channel — Dedicated messaging thread between your team and client, separate from internal chat. File sharing included.\n\nClient Reporting — Generate periodic progress summaries, budget burn, risk registers. Auto-generate on schedule and publish to portal."}]},creative_proofing:{title:"Creative Review & Proofing",icon:I.Eye,sections:[{id:"cr-1",title:"Proofing Workflow Overview",content:"Specialized review and approval workflow for visual assets — designs, layouts, videos, advertisements, marketing materials, presentations, and any creative output requiring stakeholder sign-off.\n\nUnlike general file sharing, proofing provides: version-by-version comparison, pixel-level annotation, multi-round review tracking, role-specific approval gates, and automated status progression when all required approvals are received.\n\nUpload any creative asset: images (JPG, PNG, TIFF, PSD, AI, SVG, WebP), PDFs (multi-page with navigation), videos (MP4, MOV, WebM with frame-by-frame scrubbing), and HTML pages (interactive proofs in embedded browser). Preview renditions generated automatically."},{id:"cr-2",title:"Annotation & Commenting Tools",content:"The proofing viewer provides rich annotation tools:\n\nPin Comments — Click any point to drop a pin with comment. Others see the pin and can reply as a thread. Each pin has status: Open, Resolved, Won't Fix.\n\nDrawing Tools — Rectangle, ellipse, freehand, arrow, and line tools. Configurable color and stroke. Non-destructive overlays.\n\nText Annotations — Add labels directly on the asset for corrections.\n\nMeasurement Tool — Measure distances on designs. Shows pixel values and real-world measurements if DPI metadata available.\n\nVideo-Specific: Frame-precise commenting (pause at any frame). Time-range comments for video segments. Playback speed control, frame stepping, audio waveform navigation.\n\nSide-by-Side Comparison — View two versions with synchronized zoom/pan. Overlay mode with adjustable opacity. Onion skin blending. Automated pixel-diff highlighting."},{id:"cr-3",title:"Review Rounds & Approval Gates",content:"Proofs progress through numbered review rounds. Each round has: invited reviewers, deadline, required approval count, and role-based approval matrix.\n\nApproval Matrix Example: Creative Director (must approve) + Account Manager (must approve) + Client (must approve) + Legal (for regulatory materials) + Any 2 of 5 team reviewers.\n\nReviewer Actions: Approve, Approve with Changes, Request Changes (mandatory feedback), Comment Only (no vote).\n\nRound Progression: Rejection starts new round. Creator uploads revised version. Full round history shows all versions, annotations, and change summaries.\n\nAutomatic Notifications: Reviewers notified when proof ready. Creators notified when all reviews in. Overdue reviews trigger reminders and escalation.\n\nCompletion: All approvals received changes status to Approved. Optionally lock, publish to DAM, or deliver through Client Portal."}]},brand_dam:{title:"Brand Kit & Digital Assets",icon:I.Palette,sections:[{id:"bd-1",title:"Brand Kit Overview",content:"Centralized, always-current repository of brand assets and guidelines. Unlike a regular folder, the Brand Kit enforces structure, provides previews, and ensures everyone accesses latest approved versions.\n\nComponents: Logo Library — All variations (full color, monochrome, reversed, icon-only, horizontal, stacked) with usage guidelines, minimum clear space, minimum sizes, incorrect usage examples.\n\nColor Palette — Primary, secondary, accent colors with HEX, RGB, CMYK, and Pantone values grouped by context.\n\nTypography — Font files for download with specimen pages. Specify weights, line heights, letter spacing per context.\n\nImagery Style — Photography, illustration, iconography, and pattern guidelines with approved examples.\n\nVoice and Tone — Brand voice guidelines with writing examples for different contexts.\n\nAsset Download page lets anyone grab latest logos, fonts, and templates."},{id:"bd-2",title:"Digital Asset Management (DAM)",content:"Specialized management for visual and media assets:\n\nSmart Organization — Rich metadata: title, description, creator, creation date, license type, expiration, usage rights, campaign/project association, unlimited custom fields. Browse by collection, campaign, type, date, or metadata.\n\nAutomated Processing — On upload: generate thumbnails, extract metadata (EXIF, IPTC, XMP), create web-optimized versions, generate video previews, run AI auto-tagger.\n\nCollections — Static (manually curated) or dynamic (auto-populated by metadata rules). Share with teams or external partners.\n\nAsset Lifecycle — States: Draft, Review, Approved, Published, Archived, Expired. Expiration dates for limited-license assets with renewal notifications.\n\nFormat Conversion — Download in alternative formats on-demand. Specify dimensions, color space, DPI.\n\nRights Management — Track licensing: type, territories, permitted usage, expiration, cost. Warnings when using assets outside licensed parameters."},{id:"bd-3",title:"Design System & Components",content:"Living component library for software and digital product teams:\n\nComponent Documentation — Catalog every UI component with: visual preview, interactive states, code snippets (React, Vue, HTML/CSS), usage guidelines, accessibility requirements, version history.\n\nToken Management — Centralized design tokens (color, typography, spacing, radius, shadow, animation). Export to CSS custom properties, SCSS, Tailwind, JSON, iOS Swift, Android XML.\n\nFigma/Sketch Sync — Bidirectional synchronization with design tools. Component updates in Figma auto-update NexaFlow documentation.\n\nComponent Health Tracking — Monitor adoption rates and design debt (deviations from system). Code repository integration measures usage statistics.\n\nChangelog and Migration Guides — When components change, generate migration guides. Notify affected teams automatically."}]},okr_goals:{title:"OKR & Goal Tracking",icon:I.Target,sections:[{id:"ok-1",title:"OKR Framework Overview",content:"Structured goal setting and progress tracking at every level: company-wide, department, team, project, and individual.\n\nObjectives — Qualitative, ambitious goals: Become the market leader in customer satisfaction, Ship a world-class mobile experience.\n\nKey Results — Quantitative outcomes (2–5 per objective): Increase NPS from 40 to 65, Reduce crash rate to under 0.1%, Complete 3 tech talks per quarter.\n\nKey Result Types: Numeric (current vs. target), Percentage (0–100%), Currency (budget/revenue), Binary (done/not done), Custom Unit (story points, tickets).\n\nOKR Cycles — Quarterly, semi-annual, or annual. Each cycle has its own objectives. Historical cycles archived for retrospective analysis."},{id:"ok-2",title:"Goal Hierarchies & Alignment",content:"OKRs cascade through organizational hierarchy creating clear line-of-sight:\n\nCompany Objectives flow into Department Objectives flow into Team Objectives flow into Individual Objectives. Each level links upward by connecting key results to parent objectives.\n\nAlignment View — Visual tree or sunburst chart of the complete OKR hierarchy. Color-coded by progress (green = on track, yellow = at risk, red = behind). Click any node to drill down.\n\nCross-Team Dependencies — Link key results across teams. Both teams see the dependency and track progress. Alerts when linked key results fall behind.\n\nWork Package Linking — Connect key results to work packages and milestones. Progress rolls up automatically, closing the gap between strategic goals and daily work."},{id:"ok-3",title:"Check-Ins, Scoring & Retrospectives",content:"Weekly Check-Ins — Submit progress updates: current value (numeric), confidence level (green/yellow/red), written update, and optional supporting evidence.\n\nAutomated Progress — Key results linked to work packages calculate progress automatically based on task completion or story points.\n\nScoring — At cycle end, score 0.0–1.0 (Google-style): 0.0–0.3 = significant underperformance, 0.4–0.6 = progress but not fully met, 0.7–1.0 = strong achievement. Objective scores average their key results.\n\nRetrospectives — After scoring, write what went well, what didn't, lessons learned. Builds organizational knowledge for improving goal-setting.\n\nOKR Dashboard — Organization-wide visibility: overall health, objectives at risk, top-performing teams, check-in activity timeline."}]},forms_builder:{title:"Custom Form Builder",icon:I.Form,sections:[{id:"fb-1",title:"Form Builder Overview",content:"Create structured data collection forms without code. Use for: client intake, project requests, surveys, event RSVPs, bug reports, change requests, feedback, and onboarding checklists.\n\nDrag-and-drop field types: Short Text, Long Text (rich formatting), Number (with validation), Email, Phone, URL, Date, Date Range, Single Select, Multi-Select, Radio Buttons, Rating Scale, File Upload, Signature Capture, Section Headers, Hidden Fields (pre-populated), and Calculated Fields.\n\nConditional Logic — Show/hide fields based on answers. Branch into different sections by response path. Custom validation rules."},{id:"fb-2",title:"Distribution & Responses",content:"Distribution Methods: Internal (logged-in users), Public URL, Website embed (iframe/JS snippet), QR code, Email-embedded with pre-filled fields.\n\nBranding — Custom logo, color scheme, CSS, thank-you page with redirect. Public forms on custom domain.\n\nResponse Management — Response table with sortable, filterable columns. Summary dashboard: total responses, completion rate, average time, trend, and per-field analytics.\n\nNotifications — Configure recipients when form submitted: specific users, groups, or dynamic routing based on answers.\n\nExport — CSV, XLSX, or PDF. Connect to reporting dashboards. Push data via webhooks."},{id:"fb-3",title:"Form-to-Workflow Automation",content:"Auto-Create Work Packages — Map form fields to work package fields. Submissions instantly create work packages with mapped values.\n\nAuto-Assign — Route to different people based on responses. Engineering requests go to engineering PM; marketing to marketing lead.\n\nApproval Chains — Submissions trigger approval workflows. Budget requests route to manager then finance.\n\nData Pipeline — Responses feed dashboards, populate custom fields, trigger automation rules, or pipe to external systems. Example: daily standup form posts to project chat and logs against work packages.\n\nTemplate Forms — Save and clone configurations. Share across projects. Organization-wide templates for standardized processes."}]},data_rooms:{title:"Secure Data Rooms",icon:I.Lock,sections:[{id:"dr-1",title:"Data Room Overview",content:"Controlled-access virtual spaces for sharing sensitive documents during confidential processes: M&A, fundraising, legal proceedings, board governance, IP licensing, partnerships, and regulatory audits.\n\nKey differences from regular sharing: granular document-level permissions (view, download, print per document), complete audit trail, dynamic watermarking, view-only secure viewer, access expiration, NDA acceptance gates, and mandatory 2FA.\n\nCreate from main menu: set name, description, access password, NDA text, expiration date. Upload documents into folder structure. Invite participants by email with role-based access."},{id:"dr-2",title:"Access Control & Permissions",content:"Fine-grained participant roles:\n\nAdministrator — Full control, invite others, see all audit data.\n\nManager — Upload/organize documents, manage permissions.\n\nReviewer — View documents, add annotations, cannot download or print.\n\nLimited Viewer — View specific document sections only, with redacted areas blacked out.\n\nPer-Document Permissions: View, download, and print set independently per document or folder.\n\nFence View — Restricted viewport preventing screenshots. Randomized noise patterns and user email watermark.\n\nTime-Based Access — Schedule document visibility for phased disclosures.\n\nQ&A Module — Structured questions tagged to documents. Admin routes to experts. Published to all participants or kept private."},{id:"dr-3",title:"Audit Trail & Compliance",content:"Every action logged precisely:\n\nAccess Events: Who (name, email, IP, device), when (millisecond timestamps), how long per document (per-page time tracking), download/print events, watermark IDs.\n\nDocument Events: Upload, rename, move, delete, version replace, permission change.\n\nAggregate Analytics: Most-viewed documents, time per document, participant engagement, download statistics, Q&A activity.\n\nCompliance Reports — PDF format: participant list with access history, complete access log, Q&A transcripts, NDA records with timestamps and IPs, permission change history.\n\nData Retention — On close: archive, permanently delete, or transfer to regular project.\n\nLegal Hold — Prevent any deletion even by administrators during anticipated litigation."}]},api_playground:{title:"API & Developer Tools",icon:I.Code,sections:[{id:"ap-1",title:"REST API Overview",content:"Complete programmatic access to every feature. Base URL: https://your-instance.com/api/v3/\n\nAuthentication: OAuth 2.0 Bearer Token (authorization code, client credentials, device flows), API Key (per-user, configurable scopes), Basic Auth (simple scripts).\n\nFormat: JSON with UTF-8. HAL+JSON hypermedia for discoverability.\n\nRate Limits: Default 100 req/min per API key. Adjustable per user/application. Rate limit headers in every response.\n\nPagination: Offset and cursor-based. Default 20, max 500 items. Total count and navigation links included."},{id:"ap-2",title:"Interactive API Playground",content:"Built-in interactive environment for exploring and testing endpoints:\n\nEndpoint Explorer — Browse all endpoints by resource type. Each shows: HTTP method, URL pattern, parameters, request/response schemas, permission requirements.\n\nLive Request Builder — Select endpoint, fill parameters, execute with one click using current session auth. Response with syntax highlighting and collapsible JSON.\n\nCode Generation — Generate working snippets in: cURL, Python, JavaScript, Ruby, PHP, Go, Java, C#.\n\nRequest History — All playground requests saved. Re-run, modify, or use as starting points.\n\nExample Collections — Pre-built workflows: create project and add members, query work packages, upload and share files, log time in bulk.\n\nWebhook Tester — Built-in endpoint receiving incoming webhooks and displaying payloads for debugging."},{id:"ap-3",title:"SDKs, CLI & Developer Resources",content:"Official SDKs: Python (pip install nexaflow), JavaScript/TypeScript (npm install @nexaflow/sdk), Ruby, Go, PHP. Handle auth, pagination, errors, rate limiting, and type-safe models.\n\nCLI — Terminal tool: nexaflow login, nexaflow projects list, nexaflow wp create, nexaflow files upload, nexaflow time log. Supports JSON output for scripting.\n\nDeveloper Docs — Getting started guide, auth tutorial, pagination guide, filtering reference, error catalog, webhook event reference, changelog, migration guides.\n\nCustom Apps Framework — Build custom modules: add sidebar items, inject dashboard widgets, create settings pages, register action menu items, define custom field types. Package as plugins for the App Store.\n\nDeveloper Sandbox — Dedicated test instance resetting nightly with sample data. Available to Enterprise customers."}]},sustainability:{title:"Sustainability & Impact",icon:I.Leaf,sections:[{id:"su-1",title:"Environmental Impact Dashboard",content:"Track and reduce your organization's environmental impact:\n\nCarbon Footprint Tracking: Estimates CO2 from server energy, data storage, network transfer, video calls, and notification volume.\n\nDashboard shows: monthly emissions in CO2 equivalent, 12-month trend, industry benchmarks, per-project allocation, and equivalent metrics (trees planted equivalent).\n\nAdministrators input hosting provider's energy source mix (renewable percentage) for accurate calculations."},{id:"su-2",title:"Sustainable Work Practices",content:"Meeting Efficiency Score — Analyzes patterns and suggests improvements: meetings replaceable by async communication, too many attendees, missing agendas, consistently over-time. Weekly Meeting Health Report.\n\nTravel Impact Estimation — Log trips with origin/destination and transport mode. Calculate carbon emissions and suggest alternatives: video calls, trains instead of flights, carpooling.\n\nPaper Reduction Metrics — Estimate pages saved through digital workflows based on document volume and digital approval usage.\n\nSustainability Goals Integration — Connect metrics to OKR module. Set objectives like Reduce meeting hours by 15% with automatically calculated key results."},{id:"su-3",title:"ESG Reporting & Compliance",content:"Aggregate Environmental, Social, and Governance metrics:\n\nEnvironmental: Digital carbon footprint, paper savings, travel reduction, hosting energy efficiency.\n\nSocial: Diversity metrics, work-life balance indicators (overtime, after-hours patterns), engagement surveys, community contributions.\n\nGovernance: Audit trail completeness, data protection compliance, security incidents, policy acknowledgment tracking.\n\nReport Generation — Standardized frameworks: GRI, SASB, custom formats. Auto-pull data from all modules.\n\nThird-Party Verification — Export raw data (CSV, JSON) for auditors: timestamped records, methodology documentation, confidence intervals."}]},security:{title:"Security & Compliance",icon:I.Shield,sections:[{id:"sc-1",title:"Security Architecture",content:"Defense-in-depth design:\n\nTransport: TLS 1.3, HSTS headers, certificate pinning in mobile apps.\n\nStorage: AES-256 at rest for all data. Encryption keys via HSM or software management. Separate encryption for files, metadata, and audit logs.\n\nApplication: Input validation, CSP headers, CSRF tokens, rate limiting on auth endpoints, automated dependency scanning.\n\nInfrastructure: Minimal attack surface, intrusion detection, automatic patching, regular external penetration testing."},{id:"sc-2",title:"Audit Logging & Monitoring",content:"Every significant action recorded: authentication events, file operations, work package lifecycle, permission changes, admin actions, and every API call.\n\nLog Details: Timestamp (UTC, millisecond), actor, action type, target resource, source IP, user agent, before/after values.\n\nSearch and Filter: Query by any field combination. Full-text search. Date range. Save frequent queries.\n\nSIEM Integration: Export to Splunk, ELK, QRadar, Sentinel via syslog, webhooks, or file export.\n\nImmutable Logs (Enterprise): Cryptographically signed, append-only. Cannot be modified or deleted by anyone.\n\nAlerting: Multiple failed logins, unusual locations, bulk downloads, privilege escalation, after-hours access to sensitive projects."},{id:"sc-3",title:"Compliance & Data Protection",content:"GDPR: DPA available. Right to Access (one-click export). Right to Erasure. Consent management. Data portability. Processing records.\n\nSOC 2 Type II: Annual audits for Enterprise Cloud. Reports available under NDA.\n\nISO 27001: Enterprise editions align with requirements.\n\nHIPAA: Enterprise edition configurable for healthcare data. BAA available.\n\nData Residency: Self-hosted for full control. Cloud regions: EU (Frankfurt), US (Virginia, Oregon), Asia-Pacific (Singapore, Sydney).\n\nRetention Policies: Configurable per content type. Legal hold overrides prevent deletion.\n\nPenetration Testing: Annual external tests. Responsible disclosure program. Bug bounty. Security advisories published."}]},settings:{title:"Settings & Customization",icon:I.Gear,sections:[{id:"st-1",title:"Personal Preferences",content:"Appearance: Theme (Light, Dark, High Contrast Light/Dark, System Auto). Accent color picker. Font size scaling (75%–200%). Reduced motion toggle. Compact mode.\n\nLanguage and Region: Interface language (60+). Date format. Time format. First day of week. Number format. Timezone.\n\nNotifications: Global defaults for email (immediate/hourly/daily/weekly digest), push, and in-app. Per-event-type overrides: mentions, assignments, due dates, shares, comments, announcements. Quiet hours configuration.\n\nPrivacy: Online status visibility. Profile visibility. Activity stream visibility. Read receipt opt-in/out."},{id:"st-2",title:"Project Configuration",content:"General: Project name, identifier, description, homepage, status (active/archived), parent project.\n\nModules: Enable/disable per project. Available: Work Packages, Wiki, Files, Calendar, Chat, Meetings, News, Forums, Documents, Time Tracking, Budgets, Boards, Gantt, Roadmap, Client Portal, Creative Proofing, Data Room, Forms, OKR.\n\nMembers: Add users/groups. Assign roles. Manage invitations. Member list shows name, role(s), last active, contributions.\n\nWork Package Types: Select available types. Configure defaults, required fields, auto-number sequences.\n\nCategories: Project-specific categories (Frontend, Backend, Design, Documentation).\n\nVersions: Manage sprints/releases with target dates and statuses.\n\nCustom Fields: Enable which fields appear on work packages, projects, and time entries."},{id:"st-3",title:"System Administration",content:"Users and Permissions: Manage all accounts, roles, groups, auth settings. Self-registration policy. Password requirements. Session management.\n\nProjects: View all projects. Create templates. Set default modules. Configure custom fields.\n\nWork Package Config: Define types, statuses, priorities, workflows, custom fields, required fields.\n\nEmail: SMTP settings. Notification templates. Email-to-task addresses.\n\nBranding: Custom logo, app name, favicon, login background, email header/footer, custom CSS.\n\nSystem Info: Server status (CPU, memory, disk), background jobs, connected services, health checks, error logs.\n\nBackup: Automated schedules (database + files). Manual download. Point-in-time recovery.\n\nPlugins: Install, update, configure, remove. Compatibility status."},{id:"st-4",title:"Integrations Marketplace",content:"Source Code: GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket — link repos, commits reference work packages, PR status checks.\n\nCI/CD: Jenkins, CircleCI, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Azure Pipelines — build/deploy status on work packages.\n\nCommunication: Slack, Teams, Mattermost, Discord — bidirectional notifications, create work packages from chat.\n\nCloud Storage: Google Drive, OneDrive, Dropbox, Box, S3 — mount storage, link files.\n\nCRM: Salesforce, HubSpot, Pipedrive — link client records, sync contacts, trigger projects from deals.\n\nDesign: Figma, Sketch, Adobe CC — embed previews, link frames to tasks, change notifications.\n\nAnalytics: Google Analytics, Mixpanel, Amplitude — embed dashboards, link to OKR key results.\n\nAutomation: Zapier, Make, n8n, Power Automate — connect 5000+ apps.\n\nSSO: Okta, Azure AD, OneLogin, KeyCloak, Google Workspace, PingIdentity, Auth0.\n\nCustom: Build with REST API, webhooks, or Custom Apps Framework. Distribute through internal marketplace."}]}};

// ─── NAV ───
const NAV=[{id:"home",label:"Home",icon:I.Home},{id:"getting_started",label:"Getting Started",icon:I.Rocket},{id:"file_management",label:"File Management",icon:I.Folder},{id:"project_management",label:"Project Management",icon:I.Board},{id:"collaboration",label:"Collaboration",icon:I.Chat},{id:"user_management",label:"Team & Users",icon:I.Users},{id:"calendar_time",label:"Calendar & Time",icon:I.Cal},{id:"ai_assistant",label:"AI Co-Pilot",icon:I.Ai,badge:"NEW"},{id:"automation",label:"Workflow Automation",icon:I.Zap,badge:"NEW"},{id:"client_portal",label:"Client Portal",icon:I.Globe,badge:"NEW"},{id:"creative_proofing",label:"Creative Proofing",icon:I.Eye,badge:"NEW"},{id:"brand_dam",label:"Brand Kit & DAM",icon:I.Palette,badge:"NEW"},{id:"okr_goals",label:"OKR & Goals",icon:I.Target,badge:"NEW"},{id:"forms_builder",label:"Form Builder",icon:I.Form,badge:"NEW"},{id:"data_rooms",label:"Secure Data Rooms",icon:I.Lock,badge:"NEW"},{id:"api_playground",label:"API & Dev Tools",icon:I.Code,badge:"NEW"},{id:"sustainability",label:"Sustainability",icon:I.Leaf,badge:"NEW"},{id:"security",label:"Security",icon:I.Shield},{id:"settings",label:"Settings",icon:I.Gear}];

// ─── SIDEBAR ───
function Sidebar({page,setPage,expanded,toggle,scrollTo,open,setOpen}){
  return(<nav style={{width:272,minWidth:272,height:"100vh",position:"sticky",top:0,background:"#08090d",borderRight:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05)",display:"flex",flexDirection:"column",zIndex:100}}>
    <div style={{padding:"20px 16px 16px",borderBottom:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05)"}}>
      <div style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:10}}>
        <div style={{width:34,height:34,borderRadius:9,background:"linear-gradient(140deg,#e07a3a,#d44a7a,#8b5cf6)",display:"flex",alignItems:"center",justifyContent:"center",fontSize:15,fontWeight:900,color:"#fff"}}>N</div>
        <div><div style={{fontSize:14.5,fontWeight:800,color:"#ededf5",letterSpacing:"-0.03em"}}>NexaFlow</div>
        <div style={{fontSize:10.5,color:"#555570",fontWeight:600,letterSpacing:"0.02em"}}>PLATFORM MANUAL v3.2</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div style={{flex:1,overflowY:"auto",padding:"8px 6px",scrollbarWidth:"thin",scrollbarColor:"#1a1a2e transparent"}}>
      {NAV.map(n=>{const active=page===n.id;const pg=P[n.id];const hasSec=pg?.sections?.length>0;const exp=expanded[n.id];const Icon=n.icon;
        return(<div key={n.id} style={{marginBottom:1}}>
          <button onClick={()=>{setPage(n.id);if(hasSec)toggle(n.id);setOpen(false);}} style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:9,width:"100%",padding:"8px 10px",borderRadius:7,border:"none",cursor:"pointer",background:active?"rgba(224,122,58,0.1)":"transparent",color:active?"#e8a87c":"#75758a",fontSize:13,fontWeight:active?650:500,textAlign:"left",transition:"all 0.15s"}}
            onMouseEnter={e=>{if(!active){e.currentTarget.style.background="rgba(255,255,255,0.03)";e.currentTarget.style.color="#a0a0b5";}}}
            onMouseLeave={e=>{if(!active){e.currentTarget.style.background="transparent";e.currentTarget.style.color="#75758a";}}}>
            <span style={{opacity:active?1:0.7}}><Icon/></span>
            <span style={{flex:1}}>{n.label}</span>
            {n.badge&&<span style={{fontSize:9,fontWeight:800,padding:"2px 6px",borderRadius:4,background:active?"rgba(224,122,58,0.2)":"rgba(139,92,246,0.15)",color:active?"#e8a87c":"#a78bfa",letterSpacing:"0.04em"}}>{n.badge}</span>}
            {hasSec&&<span style={{opacity:0.4,transition:"transform 0.2s",transform:exp?"rotate(0)":"rotate(-90deg)"}}><I.ChevD/></span>}
          </button>
          {hasSec&&exp&&active&&(<div style={{marginLeft:18,borderLeft:"1.5px solid rgba(224,122,58,0.15)",paddingLeft:10,margin:"4px 0 4px 18px"}}>
            {pg.sections.map(s=>(<button key={s.id} onClick={()=>scrollTo(s.id)} style={{display:"block",width:"100%",textAlign:"left",padding:"5px 8px",border:"none",borderRadius:5,background:"transparent",color:"#606078",fontSize:12,fontWeight:500,cursor:"pointer",transition:"all 0.12s",lineHeight:1.4}}
              onMouseEnter={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.color="#e8a87c";e.currentTarget.style.background="rgba(224,122,58,0.06)";}}
              onMouseLeave={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.color="#606078";e.currentTarget.style.background="transparent";}}>{s.title}</button>))}
          </div>)}
        </div>);})}
    </div>
    <div style={{padding:"14px 16px",borderTop:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04)",fontSize:10.5,color:"#3a3a50",lineHeight:1.5}}>
      <div>Updated March 2026</div><div>NexaFlow Inc.</div>
    </div>
  </nav>);
}

// ─── HOME ───
function HomePage({go}){
  const cats=[{label:"Core Platform",items:NAV.filter(n=>!n.badge&&n.id!=="home")},{label:"Advanced & Unique Modules",items:NAV.filter(n=>n.badge)}];
  const colors={getting_started:"#e07a3a",file_management:"#10b981",project_management:"#3b82f6",collaboration:"#ec4899",user_management:"#06b6d4",calendar_time:"#f59e0b",ai_assistant:"#8b5cf6",automation:"#f43f5e",client_portal:"#14b8a6",creative_proofing:"#d946ef",brand_dam:"#f97316",okr_goals:"#22d3ee",forms_builder:"#84cc16",data_rooms:"#6366f1",api_playground:"#ef4444",sustainability:"#10b981",security:"#6b7280",settings:"#78716c"};
  const stats=[{n:"19",l:"Chapters"},{n:"80+",l:"Sections"},{n:"60+",l:"Languages"},{n:"200+",l:"Integrations"}];
  const totalSections = Object.values(P).reduce((a,p)=>a+(p.sections?.length||0),0);
  return(<div>
    <div style={{padding:"56px 44px 48px",position:"relative",overflow:"hidden",background:"linear-gradient(160deg,#0c0c14 0%,#160f1e 40%,#1a0f14 70%,#0c0c14 100%)",borderBottom:"1px solid rgba(224,122,58,0.1)"}}>
      <div style={{position:"absolute",top:-120,right:-80,width:450,height:450,background:"radial-gradient(circle,rgba(224,122,58,0.08) 0%,transparent 65%)",borderRadius:"50%"}}/>
      <div style={{position:"absolute",bottom:-100,left:100,width:350,height:350,background:"radial-gradient(circle,rgba(139,92,246,0.06) 0%,transparent 65%)",borderRadius:"50%"}}/>
      <div style={{position:"relative",zIndex:1,maxWidth:680}}>
        <div style={{display:"inline-flex",alignItems:"center",gap:6,padding:"4px 12px",borderRadius:100,background:"rgba(224,122,58,0.1)",border:"1px solid rgba(224,122,58,0.15)",fontSize:11.5,fontWeight:700,color:"#e8a87c",marginBottom:20}}>
          <span style={{width:5,height:5,borderRadius:"50%",background:"#e07a3a"}}/>v3.2 — {NAV.length-1} Chapters · {totalSections} Sections
        </div>
        <h1 style={{fontSize:40,fontWeight:900,color:"#f2f0f5",margin:"0 0 14px",lineHeight:1.12,letterSpacing:"-0.035em"}}>
          Complete User Manual for{" "}<span style={{background:"linear-gradient(135deg,#e07a3a,#d44a7a,#8b5cf6)",WebkitBackgroundClip:"text",WebkitTextFillColor:"transparent"}}>NexaFlow Platform</span>
        </h1>
        <p style={{fontSize:15.5,color:"#858598",lineHeight:1.75,margin:0,maxWidth:540}}>Everything your team needs — files, projects, AI assistance, workflow automation, client portals, creative proofing, goal tracking, data rooms, sustainability reporting, and more.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div style={{display:"grid",gridTemplateColumns:"repeat(4,1fr)",borderBottom:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04)"}}>
      {stats.map((s,i)=>(<div key={i} style={{padding:"20px 24px",borderRight:i<3?"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04)":"none",textAlign:"center"}}>
        <div style={{fontSize:26,fontWeight:900,color:"#e07a3a",letterSpacing:"-0.03em"}}>{s.n}</div>
        <div style={{fontSize:11.5,color:"#606078",fontWeight:600,marginTop:2}}>{s.l}</div>
      </div>))}
    </div>
    <div style={{padding:"36px 44px 52px"}}>
      {cats.map((cat,ci)=>(<div key={ci} style={{marginBottom:36}}>
        <h2 style={{fontSize:13,fontWeight:800,color:"#555570",margin:"0 0 16px",textTransform:"uppercase",letterSpacing:"0.1em"}}>{cat.label}</h2>
        <div style={{display:"grid",gridTemplateColumns:"repeat(auto-fill,minmax(260px,1fr))",gap:12}}>
          {cat.items.map(n=>{const Icon=n.icon;const c=colors[n.id]||"#6b7280";const pg=P[n.id];const sc=pg?.sections?.length||0;
            return(<button key={n.id} onClick={()=>go(n.id)} style={{padding:"20px",borderRadius:10,border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05)",background:"#0e0e18",cursor:"pointer",textAlign:"left",transition:"all 0.2s",position:"relative"}}
              onMouseEnter={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.borderColor=c+"35";e.currentTarget.style.transform="translateY(-1px)";}}
              onMouseLeave={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(255,255,255,0.05)";e.currentTarget.style.transform="none";}}>
              <div style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:10,marginBottom:10}}>
                <div style={{width:32,height:32,borderRadius:8,background:c+"12",display:"flex",alignItems:"center",justifyContent:"center",color:c}}><Icon/></div>
                <div style={{fontSize:14,fontWeight:700,color:"#dddde8",flex:1}}>{n.label}</div>
                {n.badge&&<span style={{fontSize:8.5,fontWeight:800,padding:"2px 5px",borderRadius:3,background:"rgba(139,92,246,0.15)",color:"#a78bfa"}}>NEW</span>}
              </div>
              <div style={{fontSize:12,color:"#606078",lineHeight:1.5}}>{sc} section{sc!==1?"s":""} · {pg?.sections?.map(s=>s.title).slice(0,2).join(", ")}{sc>2?"...":""}</div>
              <div style={{position:"absolute",bottom:16,right:16,color:c,opacity:0.3}}><I.Arrow/></div>
            </button>);})}
        </div>
      </div>))}
    </div>
  </div>);
}

// ─── CONTENT ───
function ContentPage({data,pageId,go}){
  const Icon=data.icon;const idx=NAV.findIndex(n=>n.id===pageId);const prev=idx>0?NAV[idx-1]:null;const next=idx<NAV.length-1?NAV[idx+1]:null;
  return(<div style={{maxWidth:800,margin:"0 auto",padding:"36px 44px 56px"}}>
    <div style={{marginBottom:36}}>
      <div style={{display:"inline-flex",alignItems:"center",gap:7,padding:"5px 12px",borderRadius:7,background:"rgba(224,122,58,0.07)",border:"1px solid rgba(224,122,58,0.12)",color:"#e8a87c",fontSize:12,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:14}}><Icon/>{data.title}</div>
      <h1 style={{fontSize:30,fontWeight:900,color:"#f0eff5",margin:0,letterSpacing:"-0.03em"}}>{data.title}</h1>
    </div>
    {data.sections&&(<div style={{padding:"16px 20px",borderRadius:10,background:"rgba(224,122,58,0.03)",border:"1px solid rgba(224,122,58,0.08)",marginBottom:36}}>
      <div style={{fontSize:11,fontWeight:800,color:"#e8a87c",marginBottom:10,textTransform:"uppercase",letterSpacing:"0.08em"}}>On This Page — {data.sections.length} Sections</div>
      {data.sections.map((s,i)=>(<a key={s.id} href={"#"+s.id} onClick={e=>{e.preventDefault();document.getElementById(s.id)?.scrollIntoView({behavior:"smooth",block:"start"});}}
        style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:8,padding:"6px 0",color:"#808098",fontSize:13,textDecoration:"none",fontWeight:500,transition:"color 0.12s"}}
        onMouseEnter={e=>e.currentTarget.style.color="#e0dce8"} onMouseLeave={e=>e.currentTarget.style.color="#808098"}>
        <span style={{color:"#e07a3a",fontSize:10.5,fontWeight:800,fontFamily:"'JetBrains Mono',monospace",minWidth:22}}>{String(i+1).padStart(2,"0")}</span>{s.title}
      </a>))}
    </div>)}
    {data.sections?.map((s,i)=>(<section key={s.id} id={s.id} style={{marginBottom:44,scrollMarginTop:20}}>
      <div style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:10,marginBottom:14}}>
        <span style={{fontSize:10,fontWeight:900,color:"#e07a3a",fontFamily:"'JetBrains Mono',monospace",padding:"3px 7px",borderRadius:5,background:"rgba(224,122,58,0.08)"}}>{String(i+1).padStart(2,"0")}</span>
        <h2 style={{fontSize:20,fontWeight:800,color:"#e4e2ec",margin:0,letterSpacing:"-0.02em"}}>{s.title}</h2>
      </div>
      <div style={{fontSize:14,color:"#9898ad",lineHeight:1.9,paddingLeft:36}}>
        {s.content.split("\n\n").map((para,pi)=>(<p key={pi} style={{margin:"0 0 14px"}}>
          {para.split(/((?:^|\n)[\w\s/&().:+#@—–\-,']+\s—\s)/).map((seg,si)=>{
            if(/^[\w\s/&().:+#@—–\-,']+\s—\s/.test(seg.trim())){const[term]=seg.split(" — ");
              return <span key={si}><span style={{color:"#ccc8d8",fontWeight:650}}>{term.trim()}</span><span style={{color:"#606078"}}> — </span></span>;}
            return seg.split(/(\d+\.\s)/).map((it,ii)=>{if(/^\d+\.\s$/.test(it))return <span key={ii} style={{color:"#e07a3a",fontWeight:700}}>{it}</span>;return <span key={ii}>{it}</span>;});
          })}
        </p>))}
      </div>
    </section>))}
    <div style={{display:"flex",justifyContent:"space-between",gap:14,marginTop:52,paddingTop:28,borderTop:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04)"}}>
      {prev&&prev.id!=="home"?(<button onClick={()=>go(prev.id)} style={{flex:1,padding:"14px 18px",borderRadius:10,border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)",background:"#0e0e18",cursor:"pointer",textAlign:"left",transition:"all 0.15s"}}
        onMouseEnter={e=>e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(224,122,58,0.2)"} onMouseLeave={e=>e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(255,255,255,0.06)"}>
        <div style={{fontSize:10.5,color:"#555570",marginBottom:4,fontWeight:600}}>← Previous</div>
        <div style={{fontSize:13.5,color:"#b8b8cc",fontWeight:700}}>{prev.label}</div>
      </button>):<div style={{flex:1}}/>}
      {next?(<button onClick={()=>go(next.id)} style={{flex:1,padding:"14px 18px",borderRadius:10,border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)",background:"#0e0e18",cursor:"pointer",textAlign:"right",transition:"all 0.15s"}}
        onMouseEnter={e=>e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(224,122,58,0.2)"} onMouseLeave={e=>e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(255,255,255,0.06)"}>
        <div style={{fontSize:10.5,color:"#555570",marginBottom:4,fontWeight:600}}>Next →</div>
        <div style={{fontSize:13.5,color:"#b8b8cc",fontWeight:700}}>{next.label}</div>
      </button>):<div style={{flex:1}}/>}
    </div>
  </div>);
}

// ─── APP ───
export default function App(){
  const[page,setPage]=useState("home");const[expanded,setExpanded]=useState({});const[open,setOpen]=useState(false);
  const[q,setQ]=useState("");const[results,setResults]=useState([]);const[showSearch,setShowSearch]=useState(false);
  const[readPct,setReadPct]=useState(0);const mainRef=useRef(null);
  const go=useCallback(id=>{setPage(id);setExpanded(p=>({...p,[id]:true}));if(mainRef.current)mainRef.current.scrollTop=0;},[]);
  const toggle=id=>setExpanded(p=>({...p,[id]:!p[id]}));
  const scrollTo=sid=>setTimeout(()=>document.getElementById(sid)?.scrollIntoView({behavior:"smooth",block:"start"}),50);
  useEffect(()=>{if(!q.trim()){setResults([]);return;}const lq=q.toLowerCase();const r=[];
    Object.entries(P).forEach(([pid,pg])=>{if(pg.sections)pg.sections.forEach(s=>{if(s.title.toLowerCase().includes(lq)||s.content.toLowerCase().includes(lq)){
      const idx=s.content.toLowerCase().indexOf(lq);const snip=idx>=0?"…"+s.content.substring(Math.max(0,idx-30),idx+70)+"…":s.content.substring(0,80)+"…";
      r.push({pid,sid:s.id,title:s.title,pTitle:pg.title,snip});}});});setResults(r.slice(0,10));},[q]);
  useEffect(()=>{const h=e=>{if((e.metaKey||e.ctrlKey)&&e.key==="k"){e.preventDefault();setShowSearch(s=>!s);}if(e.key==="Escape")setShowSearch(false);};
    window.addEventListener("keydown",h);return()=>window.removeEventListener("keydown",h);},[]);
  useEffect(()=>{const el=mainRef.current;if(!el)return;const h=()=>{const p=el.scrollHeight-el.clientHeight;setReadPct(p>0?Math.round(el.scrollTop/p*100):0);};
    el.addEventListener("scroll",h,{passive:true});return()=>el.removeEventListener("scroll",h);},[]);
  const data=P[page];
  return(<div style={{display:"flex",minHeight:"100vh",background:"#0a0a12",color:"#c0c0d0"}}>
    <style>{`@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=DM+Sans:ital,opsz,wght@0,9..40,300;0,9..40,400;0,9..40,500;0,9..40,600;0,9..40,700;0,9..40,800;0,9..40,900&display=swap');
      @import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;600;800&display=swap');
      *{box-sizing:border-box;margin:0;padding:0;font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif;}
      ::-webkit-scrollbar{width:5px}::-webkit-scrollbar-track{background:transparent}::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb{background:#1c1c2e;border-radius:3px}
      ::selection{background:rgba(224,122,58,0.25)}
      @media(max-width:900px){.nf-sidebar{position:fixed!important;left:0;top:0;transform:translateX(-100%)!important;z-index:200!important;transition:transform 0.3s!important}
        .nf-sidebar.open{transform:translateX(0)!important}.mob-btn{display:flex!important}}`}
    </style>
    {showSearch&&(<div style={{position:"fixed",inset:0,zIndex:300,background:"rgba(0,0,0,0.6)",backdropFilter:"blur(6px)",display:"flex",justifyContent:"center",paddingTop:100}} onClick={()=>setShowSearch(false)}>
      <div style={{width:520,maxHeight:460,background:"#121220",borderRadius:14,border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)",boxShadow:"0 24px 80px rgba(0,0,0,0.5)",overflow:"hidden"}} onClick={e=>e.stopPropagation()}>
        <div style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:10,padding:"14px 18px",borderBottom:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05)"}}>
          <I.Search/><input autoFocus value={q} onChange={e=>setQ(e.target.value)} placeholder="Search all documentation…"
            style={{flex:1,border:"none",background:"none",outline:"none",color:"#e0dfe8",fontSize:14.5}}/>
          <kbd style={{padding:"2px 7px",borderRadius:4,fontSize:10,background:"rgba(255,255,255,0.05)",color:"#55556a",border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)"}}>ESC</kbd>
        </div>
        <div style={{maxHeight:380,overflowY:"auto",padding:6}}>
          {results.length>0?results.map((r,i)=>(<button key={i} onClick={()=>{go(r.pid);setShowSearch(false);setQ("");setTimeout(()=>scrollTo(r.sid),100);}}
            style={{display:"block",width:"100%",textAlign:"left",padding:"10px 14px",borderRadius:8,border:"none",background:"transparent",cursor:"pointer",transition:"background 0.12s"}}
            onMouseEnter={e=>e.currentTarget.style.background="rgba(224,122,58,0.06)"} onMouseLeave={e=>e.currentTarget.style.background="transparent"}>
            <div style={{fontSize:13,fontWeight:650,color:"#d0cee0"}}>{r.title}</div>
            <div style={{fontSize:10.5,color:"#e07a3a",marginTop:2,fontWeight:600}}>{r.pTitle}</div>
            <div style={{fontSize:11.5,color:"#606078",marginTop:3,lineHeight:1.5}}>{r.snip}</div>
          </button>)):q.trim()?<div style={{padding:20,textAlign:"center",color:"#555570",fontSize:13}}>No results for "{q}"</div>
          :<div style={{padding:20,textAlign:"center",color:"#555570",fontSize:13}}>Type to search all documentation</div>}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>)}
    {open&&<div onClick={()=>setOpen(false)} style={{position:"fixed",inset:0,background:"rgba(0,0,0,0.5)",zIndex:150}}/>}
    <Sidebar page={page} setPage={go} expanded={expanded} toggle={toggle} scrollTo={scrollTo} open={open} setOpen={setOpen}/>
    <main ref={mainRef} style={{flex:1,overflow:"auto",height:"100vh"}}>
      {page!=="home"&&<div style={{position:"sticky",top:0,zIndex:60,height:2,background:"rgba(255,255,255,0.02)"}}>
        <div style={{height:"100%",background:"linear-gradient(90deg,#e07a3a,#d44a7a,#8b5cf6)",width:readPct+"%",transition:"width 0.15s"}}/></div>}
      <div style={{position:"sticky",top:page!=="home"?2:0,zIndex:55,display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:10,padding:"10px 20px",background:"rgba(10,10,18,0.88)",backdropFilter:"blur(10px)",borderBottom:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.03)"}}>
        <button className="mob-btn" onClick={()=>setOpen(true)} style={{display:"none",border:"none",background:"none",color:"#808098",cursor:"pointer",padding:4,alignItems:"center"}}><I.Menu/></button>
        <div style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:5,fontSize:12,color:"#555570",fontWeight:500}}>
          <span style={{cursor:"pointer",transition:"color 0.12s"}} onClick={()=>go("home")} onMouseEnter={e=>e.currentTarget.style.color="#e8a87c"} onMouseLeave={e=>e.currentTarget.style.color="#555570"}>Docs</span>
          <I.ChevR/><span style={{color:"#858598"}}>{data?.title}</span>
        </div>
        <div style={{flex:1}}/>
        <button onClick={()=>setShowSearch(true)} style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:7,padding:"6px 12px",borderRadius:7,border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)",background:"rgba(255,255,255,0.02)",color:"#606078",fontSize:12.5,cursor:"pointer",transition:"all 0.12s"}}
          onMouseEnter={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(224,122,58,0.2)";e.currentTarget.style.color="#a0a0b5";}}
          onMouseLeave={e=>{e.currentTarget.style.borderColor="rgba(255,255,255,0.06)";e.currentTarget.style.color="#606078";}}>
          <I.Search/>Search<kbd style={{padding:"1px 5px",borderRadius:3,fontSize:9.5,background:"rgba(255,255,255,0.04)",color:"#4a4a60",border:"1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05)",marginLeft:6}}>⌘K</kbd>
        </button>
      </div>
      {page==="home"?<HomePage go={go}/>:<ContentPage data={data} pageId={page} go={go}/>}
    </main>
  </div>);
}

